This entry is representative of all surveys targeting RW in the year of 2005.  This was more of an experimental year to determine effective methods to capture the species and locating where the species spawns along Pikes Point.  Three RW were captured in Fyke nets over several weeks and two RW were captured after a night long gill net set.  We learned the RW tend to utilize the southern end of the reef (just as the lake bottom becomes visible) is smaller substrate (golf ball size).  Lake trout tend to use larger substrate and often captured at the northern end of the Pikes Point reef.

Started at the downstream side of the Rt. 155A bridge and continued to the old dam slightly upstream.  Water dept/low clarity made sampling difficult.  Biologist Doug Grout said he had captured ABL here before.  No ABL found.  Habitat mostly clay and undercut banks with large fallen trees.  Reach flows through mature hemlock forest.  Doug Grout caught ABL at Rt 155A crossing while he was at UNH (40 years ago?).

Started EFISHing 200 upstream of Rte 4 Bridge to downstream side of culvert on Rt. 155A.  This is the widest part of the Oyster that weve looked for ABL so far.  Substrate   Mostly soft clay and sand with areas of compacted gravel.  LWD scattered throughout the reach.  Not really any rocks until approaching the 155A bridge. Sample area began upstream  of the Rt. 155 (Manchester Rd) bridge and ended at the first beaver dam (end point 43.1596 70.9658).  Water depths made sampling difficult.  Substrate   sand and rubble.  Similar to where we found ABL in upstream areas.   Potential reds were observed (pea size gravel (fist sized) surrounded by sand at the head of small riffles/woody debris.  Lower part of reach flooded by beavers.  Upper section mostly clay ledge and scattered boulders.  Small patches of sand.  Flows through mature forest.  FF nests observed

Sample area began upstream of the series of beaver dams where reach#3 ended.  Depths made sampling difficult.  Mix of glides and riffles.  Upstream areas became less deep.  Substrate   mostly rubble with some sand and mud.  Areas of thick softwood canopy cover.  Sample site ended at confluence of Dube Brook (43.1651  70.9664).  Some potential areas for ABL were present but the species was not found.  Upstream of Snell Rd.  Because there was relatively high water on 5/12/06.  We checked a known location of ABL to see if they shifted habitats during deeper water.  We found ABL immediately in their typical habitat (in small shallow riffles or just slightly downstream).  This may help argue that ABLs are not present in the reaches sampled earlier in the day.  No mature ABL found.

Reset fyke nets and deployed 3 gill  nets by 1615h.  (Gill nets- two 2 inch 100 and one variable mesh 100)  All fish were captured in gill nets (particulary the southern most set (2 inch net).  100% Cloud Cover.  This was the first night in a few days with suitable conditions for gill netting.  The air temp and high winds of the previous days allowed the water temperature to significantly drop.  Heavy winds were also predicted for a few days after this night.  Actually wind on 12/5/06 was a light from the SW shifting to NW at about 5mph.  19 of the RW were sampled in the southern most gill net during the first pull (about a 15 minute set).  Strong indication that the RW came onto the reef in a large school.  Nets removed by 1730h.  Final check of the fyke nets.  A strong confirmation that sampling RW with fyke nets is ineffective.  Despite a relatively good sample of RW in gill nets no RW were observed in the fyke nets.

2 Gill nets set by 1530h (one 2 inch mesh and one variable mesh net both 100).  The variable mesh net was removed at first check.  Strong winds and shallow water made tending two nets too difficult.  Wind 15-20 mph from the NW.  Skies mostly cloudy changing to 100% cloud cover.  Last RW captured at 1700h.

Two 2 inch mesh gill nets on southern end of reef.  Heavy rain sustained for most of the day ending at sampling.  100% cloud cover and no wind.  Almost all RW captured came into the gill net in pairs (M/F or F/F).  First fish sampled at 1500h with no fish after 1630.  Nets were in the water until 1800h.  Observed YOY YP and RS One SMB.  Several surfaces most likely by RT or RW.

Survey to identify species presence and community composition below existing perched culvert.  This survey was conducted to examine fish species presence at the culvert on Whitney Rd. Stream branches in one spot.  Much lower water level than in recent past.  Fine silt in stream over gravel.
Abundant waterboatmen.  Water is dark brown.  Real swampy area.  Bugs are terrible.  Very muddy and smells horrible.  Old logging around site.  Parasites on fish.

Pool at top of site slow moving and deep.  Cobble and sand mostly.  Not much cover in stream.  Area surrounded with recent logging/farmland/house lots.  Beaver active in area.  High water held fish to high density in several areas.

Original Site coordinates in middle or alder swamp went upstream in same catchment to shock.  Major construction across street from site.  Outhouse downstream from site within 10 feet of stream.  Very large BND shocked.

Nice trout Stream after boork crosses dirt driveway side culvert diverts some of the stream flow into a small former trout pond less than an acre.  Takes 1/8 of downstream flow away from brook.  This site crosses a field.  Upstream is a small hobby farm that raises cattle.  Landowner told us headwaters climb up a steep hillside/mtn.  Pond has BNDs crayfish.  Pond also has small outlet that feeds the brook again about 50 yds down below.

Old stonewalls and barbed wire present.  Lots of ferns present.  NO FISH SHOCKED.  Excellent EBT habitat no fish found perhaps the water is too warm?  Barrier to fish movement below the start of site.
Intermittent Stream.  Abundant Man made debris (car truck metal ect).  No Fish Shocked.  Branches out a lot and is only about 2 inches deep in most areas.

Someone claimed to have once caught smaller EBT slightly further upstream from here.  There appears to be beaver flowages upstream from this survey site.  Crayfish abundant but fewer fish than expected were captured.  The EBT captured was of hatchery origin.  Other species captured may indicate the stream is too warm for wild EBT survival.  Gradient/substrate decreased as we surveyed upstream (rocks/cobble to sand/gravel).  Streambank armoring abundant near crossing and near adjacent lawn.  Pools are shallow and no real presence of undercut banks.  Riparian vegetation is somewhat short indicating area was cut over in the past.
No fish shocked. Moss abundant.  Makeshift bridge sid site collapsed in stream.  Skidder trail through stream at end point.  Logging as clear and severe impact on stream.

EBT and BBH CS found in first run section.  Site ends at old dam site.  Very dark brown water.  Farm stand at start.  Substrate mostly boulders and sand.  Very worn deer trail runs along stream.  Leaches shocked.
Strange white algae found many fish around it.  Several EBT Present.  Interesting diversity of substrate (Silt cobble rubble).  Signs of recent high water many SWD present.  Undercut throughout.
No Fish Shocked.  Swamp upstream of site.  Extremely hot and humid.  Logging has had a significant impact on stream.  Substrate mostly cobble.

Exposed root systems in stream causing quintessential EBT undercuts.  Many SWD on banks from recent high water.  Many large boulders within 25 ft of stream.  Rip rap stone wall at end of site.  House adjacent and right of site.  Homeowners have targets in back of house.

Stream follows Horne Road.  Road eroding into stream.  Substrate mostly cobble and sand.  Lots of water from recent rain.  Recent road work.  Good riprarian buffer next to field.  Many YOY EBTs missed in high water.
Above where site end point is a pond was built with a board dam.  If in place the pond could get 5-6 ft deep.  Ebt seen in pond above dam dam could be a movement barrier if totally boarded.

One wild EBT captured and at leasted two more were missed.  Meandering/deep cutting stream with a high amount of fresh sand.  The undersized crossing (2 very undersized cement culverts) caused deposition of even larger amounts of fresh sand in both floodplain and stream upstream.  There are recent signs of where the previous crossing had failed (lots of road material found downstream).  The crossing created a deep downstream pool (>4 ft deep).  Stream has several undercut banks where turns are made.  Downstream area flowed through a hemlock/pine forest with minimal understory canopy.

This stream segment is downstream of the large I-295 crosssing.  Sandy meandering channel with wide flood plain.  Log jams and undercut banks sporadically present.  The Station Rd. crossing (corregated metal culvert) is perched and undersized.  A small trib that enters directly below I-295 was very warm.   Despite the similar appearance to other streams with EBT in the area no EBT were found here.  Community dominated by warm/cool water species (sunfish bass).

Followup survey from 2008 upstream site to determine extent of wild EBT population.  Very long culvert used to cross Second Street and adjacent parking lot.  There appears to be a great deal of sand (and possible salt) entering the stream because of a great deal of new development on Second Street.  Eastman Ave (in Bedford) which was downstream of the survey has a crossing that is undersized resulting in backwatering and sand deposition.  All EBT appear to be wild.

Used blocking seines.  All brook trout appeared to be wild.  This index site can be used in future evaluations of any upstream restoration project.  The stream is channalized in lower half of site likely from creation of I-293.  The stream must take >90 degree turn to enter I-293 concrete culvert.  There are signs that the culvert impounds the stream during high flow conditions.  The upper section of the site has excessive sediment with large boulders creating pools.  Minimal wood in stream with the only significant presence from a large white pine crown that recently fell at about the halfway point.

There are trails that go through this brook and also on that goes through Little Cold River just down stream of the confluence.Small woody material in stream with very few larger logs.  This survey was conducted in conjunction with the Tin Mountain Conservancy group.

Stream has a high amount of sand/pea gravel (spawning gravel) existing wood is causing the gravel to deposit frequently on upstream sides and downstream sides of smaller pools stream flows from a larger beaver bog where brook trout have been observed no crossings further upstream difficult to catch brook trout (not getting stunned to well) this stream is part of a NRCS/Tin Mountain Conservancy wood addition project-wood added for 1000 yards this survey location was at the downstream end of the wood addition project EBT primarily caught under undercut banks and pools upper half of survey had slightly higher gradient and larger substrate riparian area consists of a mix of hemlocks red maple white birch ash-understory is very open.

Nice little stream that is very low with undercut banks.  Channel has moved around in pass still reminents of old channels bed on river right at start of sampling area.  Mostly small wood material in stream a few larger down logs on the banks.  There are some older signs of logging.  Did miss some fish 110 volts wasnt shocking them enough to net.  This survey was done in conjunction with the Tin Mountain Conservancy group.
No fish found.  Brush pile blocks flow.  Culvert placement is poor stream narrow and sandy with lots of grassess.  The stream goes through a development.

East fork of stream tapers to isolated pools.  West fork becomes ledgy with high valley walls as you move upstream.  No EBT found upstream. Abundant AE.  Downstream of RR habitat becomes sandy channel through shrubby wetlands.  Landowner remembers dead sea lamprey at falls near Rollins Road (probably around 1940) also recalled herring running at Sligo Rd. (upstream end of impoundment).

The stream habitat looks similar to other streams where brook trout have been captured in the area.  Floodplain is deep meandering channel pools created by falllen trees substrate consists of more clay and less sand there is a new bridge here-cement box culvert no fish captured above crossing

Surveyed site in 2007 and found one year class of ABL (all individuals less than 60 mm) possibly due to impacts from floods.  Did EFISH survey to check current status of ABL at site.  Sampling conditions difficult (tannic water with abundant leaves in stream) but captured three individuals in multiple age classes.

One gill net was deployed along documented spawning location while other net was positioned between the northern most channel markers and sunk with larger weights.  All fish were captured in traditional net.  All 6 RW captured were found in the net almost immediately after net was deployed.  No other RW were captured during the time period nets were fishing.  Again cloud cover was thick and perhaps the heavy cloud cover trigger the RW to be on the reef earlier than previously observed.  Winds changed from light NW (~5mph) to moderate NW winds by the end of the survey.  Nets were then checked every 30 minutes.  (Survey time 1630-1930).  On RW (Male 451mm/725g had large red tumor in middle of underbelly another RW (Female 445mm/650g appeared to have been captured before (missing adipose and clipped upper caudal)).

One gill net was deployed along documented spawning location while other net was positioned between the northern most channel markers and sunk with larger weights.  All fish were captured in traditional net.  RW were captured almost immediately after net was deployed.  Perhaps the heavy cloud cover trigger the RW to be on the reef earlier than previously observed.  Winds changed from calm to light NW (~5mph) by the end of the survey.  The traditional net was checked regularly until RW capture slowed.  Nets were then checked every 30 minutes.  (Survey time 1530-1930)

Survey was conducted in an effort to verify the presence of American Eels and Walleye.  High flows from rain yesterday.  The river was turbid and deep with fast flow.  American eel were observed but difficult to capture.  No walleye observed.
Survey was conducted in an effort to verify the presence of American Eels and Walleye.  High flows from rain yesterday.  The river was turbid and deep with fast flow.  No walleye or eel observed.

Orange algae covering stream bottom.  Bottom mostly sand.  Abundant trash.  One section had eroding banks with soil washing into the stream.  Crossings at both ends of reach.  Theres an inlet perch at the downstream end of the cement culvert (long- ~100ft) on Ash Street.  The survey ended at a covered section of Berry Brook (perhaps and old crossing) behind a residential house on Maple St.
Stream is very entrenched with minimal or now buffer.  Much of this section has lawn up to the waters edge.  Stream has cut down up to two feet in some locations.  Very turbid with iron color.

Surveyed up to next crossing (private/industrial crossing?).  Brook trout appear to be hatchery fish because of pectoral fin wear on both cohorts.  Much more canopy cover-clost to 100%.  Losts of garbage in stream.  Hough Rd. crossing consists of three small culverts (two are clogged with debris and no flow is going through them.  The single culvert with flow appears to be suitable for passage.  Stream is still entrenched in some places here.  Stream is very turbid and becomes completely brown when walking though it.  It likely gets this way after storm events as well.
standard warmwater assessment  hadnt been shocked before lots of vegetation around shoreline

Nice brook trout stream cobble/boulder/ledge substrate road follows stream for about 50m-probably contributing sand/fill/trash culvert slightly perched-will likely get worse over time-potential restoration banks are well vegetated  the stream flows into an overgrown meadow below road crossing.
Surrounding area was once cut over (clear cut) but a riparian buffer was left.  Wooded area has regenerated.  The gradient of the stream increased toward the end of the survey.

This tributary stream appears more flashy than the mainstream of Mink Brook.  This stream drains Moose Mtn.  Road passes near stream but far enough away (~30m) to lessen impact House along shoreline with lawn along streambank signs of bank armoring (granite ledge and stone walls) mostly embedded cobble/boulders with one ledge that creates a small waterfall majority of channel consists of a shallow riffle very few pools wood is not contributing to stream habitat here.

Wide/straight channel with embedded substrate uniform riffle habitat which may reflect historical land uses (agriculture road construction along stream and possible logging) bankful width ~12-15m suggests flashy flows-wetted width is wide and shallow (5-8m at low flow) variety of vegetation on the streambanks suggest the soils may be less acidic than waters in the Merrimack/coastal watersheds stream substrate looks similar to streams in VT Very little wood in channel Bridge is open bottom and spans channel width about 0.8*bankful width runoff from road flows directly into stream about 1/2 mile upstream there is a ~15ft waterfall that appears to be impassable to fish
Salamanders and green frogs present.  This area is currently wooded but there are signs that it has been logged in the past.
Lots of broken glass bottles old bricks car pipes.  Spoke with neighbor who has been removing trash over the years.  Crayfish frogs and worms present.

The lawns from residential housing are a clear issue here.  Only shade is from forrested valley on river left side.  Very shallow area-minimal pool presence lots of older debris from cronstruction (bricks cinder blocks ect) in stream some larger boulders create deeper habitat extensive bank modifications on downstream end (bank armoring/landscaped rock wall) bank modifications bedrock and valley shape likely prevent wood to accumulate here.
Despite being well shaded the stream was warm (20.9C).  Garbage (construction material/metal) in stream.
This site had two manmaade dams present.  The river right side of the stream consisted of ~25% mowed lawn while the left side had a lot of armoring.  The stream had lots of overhanging vegetation.

Stream is extremely entrenched/ditched small wooded buffer on both sides ~20ft then large agricultural fields livestock may once have had free access to this stream stream consists mostly of a shallow run appears to be very flashy and sediment starved lots of scour signs deeper sections mostly created by larger rocks and small wood structure this stream may have been straightened at some point signs of cutting in and near stream.

Rural/residentail area lots of exposed cobble bars that are exposed to sunlight it appears that bank armoring occurred here quite some time ago to protect the yards of nearby homeowners the yards leave minimal riparian buffers this section has deeper slowmoving pools that are not found in the higher gradient sections upstream.

Very low flow-goes intermittent upstream of Greensboro Rd.  Two crossings below Greensboro Rd (lower crossing consists of two 2ft perched pipes with a debris jam at the inlet-not being used anymore the upper crossing is used for a driveway consisting of a 3ft pipe-backwatering occurs here and appears to be passable).   Sewage smell at site-dripping pipe entering at right angle at the upper crossing If lower crossing was removed about 100ft of EBT spawning habitat may be opened up.  Lawn cut to bank at upper end of site (near Greensboro Rd) increased runoff into stream from stormwater at the end of Hollenbeck Rd EBT only caught between confluence and first crossing the last fish (CC) was caught in the pool above the second crossing.

This stream is the outlet of a large (~5acre) stormwater detention/wetland area that gets lots of sun and runoff.  Water has a white/milky color to it.  The stream became quikly turbid when walking in it.  Several suspected monitoring wells observed.  Gas or oil smell detected.  The stream is mostly all entrenched with the exception of areas with larger boulders.  Large amounts of small wood in and around stream.  High water temperature clearly an effect from wetland pond upstream.  Electrofishing unit appeared to not be fully operating.  Do not use this site for CPUE or relative abundance analysis.

Large floodplain cobble sand substrate with deep pools at bends scattered boulders.  A few EBT in pools and under fallen logs-difficult to shock in deep pools.  Possible spottail shiner.  Landowners has pictures of a wood turtle observed at the site.  Lawn mowed up to the stream causing some bank collapse.  Large drainage ditch along road flows into stream here.
Not a lot of understory because coniferous trees shade ground.  Overstory consists mainly of hemlock white pine and beech.
complaints of poor bass fishing few rocks  moderate vegetation but portions with lots of bladderwort
standard warmwater assessment,good number of downed trees lots of vegetation (milfoil)

BS very abundant in pool above bridge.  Fish concentrated in small channel in large mud flat due to drained impoundment in preparation for Bunker Pond Dam removal.  Some veg (floating heart) left in pool but most of channel through old impoundment is shallow and silty.  It will be interesting to see if BS can persist in this reduced habitat.  Also observed BS upstream of old impoundment.

Gravel/cobble substrate with exposed clay in places undercut banks common suggesting high flows in spring field mowing occurs upstream flows close enough to road for some sedimentaion to occur but not much impact overall abundant trout in pools with wood-less in pools with scared clay bottom wood not overly abundant in stream but what wood is present has formed pools

Cobble/boulder substrate channel filled with very find sand old cement dam structure several collapsed banks lawn and junk along left bank steep valley walls silt washing in from trib upstream plastic culvert w/4 foot prech at River Rd scour pool here odd home to yellow perch in small cold stream stream flows out of Lake Gardner caught 1 spring salamander sediment washing in from River Road at both the upstream and downstream ends of the culvert.

Site is in wooded area within livestock.  Pasture has multiple area of erosion where cows walk through streams.  Lots of caddis larvae and stones.  Few seeps entering at cow trails mostly riffle and runs flowing 1-2 inches deep.  Few pools mostlly 4-6 inches deep.  Stream is influenced geomorphically by cow trails and has mud running in but still brook is very productive.  Also cow manure in and along wetted stream channel and banks.

Stream is likely seasonal.  Rain last night may have added additional nontypical summer flow.  No fish only salamnders captured.  Stream appears to flow out of a swamp/wetland.  We found 2 wild EBT downstream of crossing at River Road.  The crossing is preventing fish from accessing the survey area.  Lots of runoff (gravel deposition) at crossing.

Gorge-like habitat too much current during floods for downed wood to take purchase very steep ledge banks stream flows from a wetland and under power lines and fields upstream of site canopy at site is much thicker all pools created by bedrock ledge creates channel constriction minimal floodplain here crossing (bridge) is fine-less road gravel runoff than other areas natural falls likely limit movement.

Site has large cobble/gravel/sand bars where stream goes intermittent.  Habitat is very pocketed- mostly stagnant pools full of ferric algae stream would be good if flow was better one pool full of dead salamanders leeches deer tracks present bottom of site is ~40ft pool with 3 inches depth pool is muddy and silty making it difficult to shock-lost fish.

Very small + shallow stream with minimal gradient.  Minimal depth at riffle sections.  Very wet floodplain.  Lots of YOY EBT.  Low gradient small watershed.  Road gravel runoff occuring on both sides of Lang Rd.  Slightly perched culvert - passage likely possible under most conditions.  Area logged heavily in the late 1980s.

Appears that somone constructed a few weirs/dams most BND were caught upstream of roaad relatively very few EBT YOY The lower end was once part of an old beaver impoundment below surveys site there is still a pond with lots of sun and open areas large pool directly downstream of crossing from culvert scout the pool had several EBTs tucked into overhanging vegetation at the head end of pool newer beaver dam cause the stream to flow under ground at survey start point Upstream end (above West Bath Rd)- signifigant deposition of larger materials (cobble and rubble) it is difficult to saw where this larger material comes from very shallow but there are some nice pools on the river left side created by bank cutting and root structures minimal buffer on river right side from large field.

Substrate made mostly of shale upstream portion of site wooded by mixture of hard and softwoods lower portion is more open with overhanging vegetation site has many splits in the stream crayfish macros and earth worms present.

River flows less than 15 feet from River Rd in this section with no buffer on river right side there are rock veins to redirect flow from the road.  These veins increased depth and speed we surveyed both sides of the cobble mid channel bar much more fish on the river right channel
Site is very heavily vegetated (alder grasses and ferns) cow pasture and culvert on downstream end toward Hill Rd site has lots of siltation culvert and livestock clearly having an impact on stream.

This stream may also be referred to as Starch Factory Brook.  Large development upstream flows out of Mountain Lake (1/4 mile upstream).  Boulder/cobble substrate with large wood jams  - signs of mbile cobble downstream.  Confined channel with steep valley walls and small forested floodplains.  Undercut and eroding banks downstream.  Perched culvert half filled with cement with embedded pipes (2 perch).  Iron colored seep on left bank downstream from culvert.  Good EBT habitat but unusually warm (70 degrees) due to lake upstream.  Surprising number of ATS in stream.  Sediment entering stream from road at crossing.

Stream is vell shaded by hard and softwoods and splits 1/3 of the way up due to log jam.  Past flooding events have left signs of erosion wood has changed stream morphology culvert seems to not have large impact on upstream end of stream but has a 6 inch perch and is begining to undercut material on top of culvert is starting to erode.

Stream appears channelized due to road and farm fields.  Bridge goes over sitate at 100 feet.  Site is very uniform with no major stream features- cobble/gravel substrate in about 3 of water.  Alder and willow bank vegetation.
standard warmwater assessment some rocks vegetation

The Epping Water Department has a pump facility here which may reduce flow levels.  Stream is very entrenched here.  This stream section was surveyed specifically to look for the presence of wild brook trout.  The stream was not surveyed in the 2010 Lamprey Watershed EBTJV surveys but either GIS maps indicated the presence of high ground water recharge rates or a wild brook trout was found nearby in previous surveys.

In 2010 wild EBT were found in Rum Brook- a stream in the same area.  Two YOY EBT were captured about 70m on the upstream side of the crossing.  All EBTs on downstream side were in the scour pool below the perched culvert.  Only 1 adult EBT (~160m) was found upstream of the crossing.  Both sides of the stream had minimal flow with several disconnected areas.  Upstream substrate was muck and sand while downstream substrated consisted of cobble and larger substrate. Crossings placed above streambed causing impounding upstream and major sand deposition downstream.  The crossing was recently replaced this way.  Stream is impacted by upstream chicken farm-culvertized and open field.  Some trash present in stream.  Abundant BND Algae present in slow moving areas (pools).  Sand deposition present along banks.  Stream has minimal canopy cover consisting of tall grasses.
standard warmwater assessment lots of wood  decent to sparse vegetation

Historical agriculture may have impacted stream-old electric fence crosses stream.  Survey started at a ford where vehicles are directly driven through stream to access a hay field-soft mobile substrate.  Ends at an abandoned road crossing that is a barrier to fish movement-crossing is piled rocks and masonry scrap.  Stream consists mostly of shallow pools joined by very shallow riffles.  Minimal buffer in some areas (<5ft) landscape has several fields in this valley.

This stream is heavily erroded with steep banks.  Lots of old woody material that has been cut (saw logs).  Very steep ravine brook that is well shaded.  Several parts of this reach are dry and the habitat consists of pocket waters.  Scrap metal present in stream.

Cows have free access to the upper half of the survey site.  The lower half has minimal buffer (<4ft) with one side mowed for a lawn.  The crossing below the survey site (private driveway) is perched with a very large pool containing several visible trout.  The perched crossing has a large cement apron.  The is no flow above the Coppermine Rd crossing-completely dry.  Both wild EBT and RT present cold water must offset landuse impacts.

Stream is impacted by upstream chicken farm-culvertized and open field.  Some trash present in stream.  Abundant BND Algae present in slow moving areas (pools).  Sand deposition present along banks.  Stream has minimal canopy cover consisting of tall grasses.

Sampled both tributary and mainstem of Hunt Mountain Brook.  Trib only had EBT and SS and flowed from a perched unpassable culvert.  Rt. 135/Hunt Mt. Bk crossing was long (~50ft) and consisted of an open bottom culvert (passable).  Heavy knotweed cover along mainstem (up to 15ft tall).  Mainstem relatively flat compared to tributary.  This area is very close to where the stream enters the Connecticut River.  Mainstem landscape has the typically wide valley shape.

Habitat consists of very uniform substate of cobble and rubble.  Stream is very exposed with only a few trees providing shad.  An extra 7 meters were included to add the only pool in the reach.  Very few macros.  Salamanders present.  Grasses keep bank intact.  Stream appears that it would have been dry if not for rain the day prior.  The nearby crossing consisted of a 10inch diameter pipe 30 ft long with a 4ft perch.

Trib to CT River.  This stream flows from Bent Pond (in NH) into MA before entering CT River.

BS captured in vegetation along margins of ponded area of Lamprey River upstream of Main Street bridge in Raymond.  BS less abundant and patchy in this reach compared to populations upstream.  Very few larger individuals observed.  No BS observed despite no obvious change in habitat starting about 0.35 miles upstream of Main Street bridge down to next crossing at Epping Street.  More epiphytes on veg and shift from floating heart to pondweed as dominant plant but changes are subtle.  Housing density increases significantly just downstream of ponded area.
Trib to CT River manmade rock dam at downstream end of pool.  We missed several brook trout in the pool (~20 fish) due to depth and size of pool.

Trib to CT River the stream crosses under Rt 63 above survey site stream at site is higher in elevation then drops via a waterfall then reducing in gradient.  Mudpuppy observed two small SMB observed at mouth of stream.

very small stream that is heavily wooded trib to CT River shallow/no reel pools for brook trout to over-winter in.  Small salamanders present.
area severely impacted by Hurricane Irene.  Severe road erosion and washouts upstream.  Flows were much higher than normal and water was slightly cloudy.

Unlike other runs conducted during this day that followed the NH shoreline both shorelines were surveyed because downstream sections appeared too shallow for the electrofishing boat.  This survey targeted only round whitefish.  Other species observed were noted but not captured.  One possible RW missed during this run

Habitat much different than upstream of culvert. Flatter slope. No gradient in dstr end. Alders in lower section (dstr end of site). Opens up to old bog pond area. Beaver activity present. Dam construction evident. Caddis casings abundant. Lots of animal trails/runs present.
Surveyed 50m below crossing to 50m above crossing.  Difficult to survey large pool downstream of crossing.

No trout just 1 cc and 2-lined salamander above rd. perched culvert 2 crushed water flowing over rd and along drainage ditch and over road adjacent to stream. Lots of downed trees in the stream but no deep pools except u/s culvert. Mossy banks w subsurface flow. trib entering from open alder swamp. Steep rocky gradient just u/s pool of culvert

No trout just 2 cc  high flow from last nights thunderstorm runoff  sand/gravel in stream from washed out road  1 culvert crushed and perched (~2)  water flowing along road and crosses near culvert & rejoins stream  Alder swamp at beginning of run-braided channel & many downed trees-difficult for fish to pass esp. at low flows

No trout just one CC and two line salamanders present perched culvert (2) squashed.  Water flowing over road and along drainage ditch and over road adjacent to stream.  Lost os down trees in stream but no deep pools except above culvert.  Mossy banks with subsurface flow.  Tributary entering from open alder swamp.  Steep rocky gradient just above pool at culvert.

High flow from runoff-thunderstorms overnight sand/gravel in stream from road washout 1 culvert squashed and perched about 2.  Water flowing along road and crosses near culvert and then rejoins stream.  Alder swamp at beginning of run.  Braided channel and many down trees.  Difficult for fish to get through especially at low flow.  No EBTs present just CC.

Habitat much different than upstream of crossing (undersized double culvert) flatter slope (minimal gradient at beginning) alders in lower section survey began at the head end of an old beaver pond/bog beaver dam construction evident caddis casings abundant lots of animal trains/runs present.  Minimal flow and slight perch may make passage through crossing difficult.

Conductivity extremely low very little deep pool habitat very steep gradient yellow birch black spruce balsam fir dogwood some maple EBT present in every pool several different age classes of EBT lots of cascades/water falls thick moss on rocks no sculpins.  Minimal flow and slight perch may make passage through crossing difficult.
water higher than normal
water much higher than normal
YOY bass survey index site nice rocky habitat
YOY bass survey index site nice rocky substrate
YOY bass survey index site dark water lots of weeds
YOY bass survey index site sand and rocks  good on rock outcroppings and jetties
water higher than normal
This survey was focused on obtaining genetic samples on wild brook trout for a Trout Unlimited/Antioch project.  Nontarget species were not noted.

40 squash style culvert is in the middle of site.  Upstream recently had work done to restore stream from spring flood damage.  Culvert undersized and jammed.  Water flowed over road.  Wood addition and jam created to block off flood channel .  Work completed two weeks ago so channel still new (mostly loose cobble and gravel with no wood).  Large pool at the base of the culvert downstream with sand evident in all pockets.  Sand embeds gravel cobble and rubble and is present on banks.  Roots exposed along bank on river right and cobble bars exposed on river left.  Two line salamanders present.

40 foot squash culvert in middle of site. Upstr recently had work done to restore stream from spring flood damage. Culvert undersized. Mostly loose cobble and gravel. No wood. Large pool at base of culvert. Sand evident in all pockets. Roots exposed along banks. cobble bars exposed on RL. 2-line salamanders

green frogs present site is high elevation 2 waterfalls downstream of culvert and 2 u/s-could be barriers site is heavily forested-lots of downed wood,u/s appears steeper than d/s mostly soft woods and yellow birch lagr substrate.  D/s slightly flatter slope more percentage of rubble/cobble canopy predominant alder. Culvert definitely undersized-which impacts/endangers effects roadway. male ebt milting and females soft

Alder spruce firs white and yellow birch culvert slightly perched and undersized culvert blew out 3 years ago likely because the crossing is not inline with the stream channelit forces the stream to bend 90 degrees

Alder Spruce Firs White Birch Yellow Birch Culvert slightly perched and definitely undersized. EBT choked up earthworm. Culvert blew out 3 years ago could be because of 90 degree corner in stream channel just upstream of culvert.

Surveyed 160 upstream and downstream of 25 round culvert.  Stream heavily covered in Alder downstream and softwoods upstream.  Green frogs present.  Site is high elevation.  Two waterfalls downstream and upstream of crossing.  Heavily wooded site.  Upstream appears steeper than downstream with larger substrate.  Downstream site has small rubble/cobble substrate.  Crossing condition threatens road.  Both male and female EBT are close to spawning.
water higher than normal

Quickly surveyed above and below culvert.  Caught 1 FF and 1 EBT (adult female with eggs possibly wild) about 50m downstream of crossing.  Local resident said upstream goes dry.  Signs of sediment from road washout.  Scour pool below double culvert.  Should resurvey - why so few stream fish in November?

Gill nets deployed parallel to each other with the spawning reef between the two nets. Nets set between 1400-1730h.  Winds initially 20+mph then going to a steady 5-10 mph NW.  Both fish caught immediately.  No milt found with either fish.  Winds made net placement and visual ID of spawning substrate difficult

Gill nets deployed parallel to each other with the spawning reef between the two nets.  Calm/very foggy.  Nets set between 1500-1730.  No RW captured (2 fallfish in net).  Possibly observed RW swimming but not captured.  Very cloudy and dark all day.  Perhaps RW spawned during the day.

Gill nets deployed parallel to each other with the spawning reef between the two nets.  Calm cloudy foggy with off and on rain.  Nets set between 1200-1600h.  3 RW caught immediately and 4 other RW tricked in slowly.  All females ripe.  Two RW were likely caught in previous years (caudal clip visible).

Gill nets deployed parallel to each other with the spawning reef between the two nets.  Light west wind and partly cloudy.  Three possible recaps from previous years (caudal clip visible).  Water was very slow to cool this year (mild fall temperatures).
The presence of a Koi was reported to fish and game.  An electrofishing boat was used to capture and remove the koi.  Other species present were noted.

Small stream with very mobile sand substrate.  Extensive undercut banks and small wood common in stream.  This made cathcing brook trout difficult.  Nearby business said the area was recently impounded by a beaver dam.  Old stream channels were visible.  Logging and gravel operation on river right side.  Most brook trout were in slightly deeper pools created by smaller wood and bends.  Only brook trout were captured.

Channel with deep water made electrofishing difficult.  Shallow areas were targeted to get a sense of fish species presence.  Two larger LMB were observed in channel but not captured.  This location is near the confluence with the Warner River and I-89.  Large silver maple flood plain fish have easy access in and out of the Warner River here.  Warm surface temperatures flowing out of Tom Pond likely preclude wild EBT presence here.  Fish data should not be used here to compare CPUE.

A few crayfish present.  Despite their small size brook trout appeared to be in good condition.  The undersized crossing on Kearsarge Rd created a large/deep pool that was too deep to survey.  Stream is very muddy/mucky and has a wetland floodplain that is very lush.  Stream is narrow but gets wider at bends.  Culvert may become perched during low flow conditions.  Stream substrate is very fine (gravel and sand).  Good riparian buffer in survey location (at least 100 on both sides of stream) between stream and nearby Hopkinton fairgrounds.

There is a lot of loose sediment in the upstream section of the survey location.  It is likely that a beaver dam recently blew out or was removed.  The survey site also had a smaller beaver dam (2 feet high).  Lower section of survey location had more coarse substrate with a lot less sand.  Deeper channel in upper section made electrofishing somewhat difficutl.  Runoff/sediment from road directed into stream near intersection.

Two streams merge just above survey end point.  The larger tributary flows out of a very large beaver pond.  The other tributary is much more smaller and may be seasonal during drought years.  Both streams were quickly checked for wild brook trout presence (above survey end point) and none where found only BND present.  Mink Brook Ln crossing consists of a large crushed pipe that has been recently repaired with a cement pad on the bottom.  This has created a perched outlet and no sediment or habitat features inside the crosssing.  Very shallow depth through crossing.  The stream has a good riparian buffer but an active logging operation has opened up some of the shading canopy in one location.  Stream doesnt really access floodplain (downcut overtime).  Surveyed pool below crossing (below survey site) and only found CWS and BND.  The liklihood of wild EBT recolonization is low because of the barriers along Siliver Brook.  There is an impounded section (Silver Pond) that was once a water supply and now a swimming/recreation area.  There are good examples of road drainage being directed well away from stream here (see photos).

Stream flows through a well forested area and mainly only exposed to sun near road crossings.  Several different types of species present helps to explain some influence from wetlands upstream but water temperatures appear to be suitable for wild brook trout.  The stream crosses Red Chimney Rd several times.

No fish captured but salamanders and macroinvertebrates were abundant.  Difficult to tell if stream is seasonal because of the rain from yesterday.  Channel splits into two smaller streams above survey location (above crossing).  Crossing consists of gathered rocks so vehichles can cross stream on the class VI road.  Most of the flow travels through a vortex between the rocks.  Signs of older logging along stream.  Stonewalls from historical agriculture observed.  Some mature trees still exist but much of the canopy is from younger trees (20-30 years old).  Stream looked suitable for wild EBT but not found.  Perhaps there is a barrier downstream that blocks recolonization.  The large amount of scour indicates the stream can be very flashy.
This site was sampled for a pre dam removal investigation.  Caddis fly and black fly larvae

Crossing (end of survey) is made from stone blocking.  There have been recent repairs to it where road runoff has scoured away both sides of crossing.  Former bridge material (cobble and rubble) have washed downstream up to 30 yards from crossing.  Despite recent rainfall and runoff issues water is very clear.  A tributary stream that enters the larger stream also contains brook trout.  YOY brook trout were so small they fell through mesh on dip nets.

Slow wide deep stream that made electrofishing difficult.  Fish were observed in stream but were not affected by sampling gear.  Sampling was restricted to shallow areas.  Only one ECP was captured.  Stream is the outlet of Lake Winnipocket.  Beaver sign along study area.  Suitable riparian buffer throughout reach.

There is some seepage discharging from the ground into the stream from the direction of the home with the livestock.  Did not notice any odor.  Perched culvert at crossing.  Small foot bridge in the middle of reach.  Tee pee near stream.

Stream flows from Night Hollow Marsh and likely too warm for wild EBT.  Possible sand runoff from nearby dirt road.  Series of runs intermixed with a few drops.  Recent logging on river right side opens up canopy.  Crossing is not perched but may be a little small.  Coarse substrate reduces the ability for wood to form pools.  Lots of crayfish.

Survey site was cut short due to much and loss of well established channel.  Culvert pool below Schoodac Rd is too deep to electrofish.  Stream is the outlet of Meadow Pond and has temperatures that likely are too warm for wild brook trout.  Low gradient stream that follows parallel to Schoodac Rd through survey location.  All crossings appear to offer suitable fish passage.  No noticable habitat impacts.  Stream became very turbid and took a long time to clear.  Stream has good access to adjacent wetland/floodplain.  Scale malfunctioned   weights of captured fish not available.

Stream with very mobile bed.  Wood and larger rocks have carved out pools.  Undercut banks with pools at bends and common and held a lot of wild brook trout.  Large quantitiy of spawning gravel.  Only EBTs captured.  Despite clearing for a camp canopy still provides plenty of shade.  Small foot bridge Kearsarge Mountain Rd and private crossing present no issues with fish movement.  Some trees have been cut near and within the stream.

Nice high gradient brook trout stream.  Pools created by larger rocks.  It is likely too flashy and has too large of substrate for wood to accumulate and form pools.  Good crossing for fish movement.  Stream levels off in gradient above survey location.  Wild brook trout still present above falls as high as 3 feet.

Large shallow stream consisting mostly of shallow runs with a few riffles at survey point.  Good mix of different sized substreate but most if it is embeded with sand.  Survey site is between I-89 and North Rd.  Large amound of armoring at end of survey site for road protection.  Lots of deposited sand in slow moving areas (river bends).  Heavy amound of dump truck traffic carrying sand on North Rd.

Sand and silt are entering stream near road crossing.  Several trees cut alongside banking near bridge.  This section of stream is the outlet of a large beaver impoundment.  Survey area is close to confluence with Stevens Brook.  Crossing does not appear to present fish movement issues.  A path along the stream may indicate heavy fishing pressue.

The buffer between Stevens Brook and North Rd is minimal in this location.  There are several areas where road gravel is going directly into the stream.  Road drainage directed into stream in several locations.  The edge of the road in some areas is the actual stream bank.  High abundance of crayfish present.  Several captured fish had cuts/trauma associated with crayfish.  Warm water temperatures likely preclude the presence of wild brook trout in this location.  The stream drains an extensive beaver pond/marsh system just upstream.  The two hatchery brook trout captured were in poor condition (likely from being in undesirable temperatures).

All brook trout captured are wild.  Rocks covered with moss salamanders present intermittent stream entering half way down survey reach (just a small trickle flowing from behing closest house.  Two small cascades at downstream side of Island where fish can navigate through them during higher flows.

Heavy canopy made electrofishing difficult.  Lots of crayfish.  Old stone crossing that is now abandonded does not appear to be an issue with fish passage.  Stream useds to be surrounded by open fields (stonewalls ornamental flowers and old armoring present).  Nice mix of pools and undercut banks.

Old stone mill dam upstream of site and bridge crossing.  Fish can likely pass along the side of the dam structure.  This is the outlet stream of Lake Winnipocket.  Rock wall extends from bridge downstream on the river right side of bank.

Although immediate riparian buffer allows for shading and wood addition the current landscaping practice leaves only a very narrow riparian strip to protect the stream.  Substrate is very sandy in this location.  Lots of trash/litter found in stream.  Thick alders made capturing brook trout difficult.  A high number of YOY brook trout were captured and observed.  Stream flows into Stevens Brook <100m from survey location.  It is likely that wild brook trout found here are isolated from other populations.  This may be a good opportunity/project for students to learn about brook trout ecology and stream restoration (the need for riparian buffers road runoff thermal limitations etc.).  Survey conducted during record breaking air temps. Stretch below upper crossing at end of survey location was not electrofished in order to avoid harming the population in such warm air temps.

Stream is also known as Childs Brook.  Larger trees fallen into stream were common throughout survey location.  Stream flows from Meadow Pond and may have temperatures that only offer marginal habitat for wild brook trout.  The survey occurred during a very hot day.  The presence of fish species more tolerable to warm water temperature may be an indication of marginal conditions for EBT habitat.  Hatchery brook trout captured here.  The stream is stocked for a kids fishing derby.  Crossing appears suitable for strong swimmig fish species but may become difficult if flows are reduced.

Cascades present and likely navigable during high flows.  Moss covered rocks  in stream and  along banks.  Spring seeps are present from the hillside near Newmarket Rd.  Several brook trout were missed in deeper pool.  Well established forested canopy.  Larger substrate likely precludes fallen trees to form pools.

Stream appears to flow from a wetland/pond.  All brook trout appear to be wild.  Very high gradient stream with large substrate.  Large boulders created pools.  All brook trout were found in pools.  The heavy use (worn down trails) around the stream makes it likely that the stream gets some fishing pressure.  Waterfall near confluence with the Warner River likely precludes fish passage.  Stream is likely very flashy during high flows (lots of bank scour and limited wood left in stream.  Landowners have cut a few trees very close to stream but canopy still provides almost 100% shade to stream.  Although the Rt. 103 crossing is perched the barrier should be a low priority for removal as the falls directly upstream preclude movement.

Started approximately 50 feet upstream from culvert.  Smaller stream where fallen wood has helped to created pools and meanders.  Large number of undercut banks.  Crossing near survey location appears suitable for fish passage.  This stream flows from a wetland above survey site.

This survey was conducted to gather information for a pre culvert restoration project for Trout Unlimited (Colin Lawson).  This is a presence/absence survey.  Difficult to sample.  75-100% riparian cover.  The stream meanders considerably.  Lots of woody material.

This is a tributary to Thompson Brook.  High water flows from Hurricane Irene scoured part of the reach.  Cobble and rubble moved around and likely changed the stream channel.  Spring seep entering stream about 160 feet above the crossing.  Tributary entering in near the starting point discharging from two plastic three foot culverts.  Horse property present at adjacent property.  This survey was conducted to gather information for a pre culvert restoration project for Trout Unlimited (Colin Lawson).
Good habitat rocks pools and a few trees.

This survey was conducted to gather information for a pre culvert restoration project for Trout Unlimited (Colin Lawson).  Beaver keep plugging culvert.  A lot of sand and silt deposits upstream of reach from flooding.  Stream meanders.  Culvert is passable to fish.

Lots of grass and vegetation in stream.  Gras ferns and shrubs along the entire reach of stream.  This survey was conducted to gather information for a pre culvert restoration project for Trout Unlimited (Colin Lawson).

Stream flows through state property in this location.  Many crayfish and one mudpuppy.  Appears that fish have access to and from the Connecticut River through a set of double pipes set in a vertical concrete wall.

Bedrock/large boulders in entire stream pools have sandy bottoms start of site cascading riffle down approx. 40 feet down end of site has falls approx. 5 feet tall little organic material in stream but some along banks at times of high flow

High gradient stream with large substrate minimal spawning substrate lots of bedrock with shallow depths drainage for road well directed away from stream stream can be very flashy- lots of undercut banks with side channels (at high flow) stream appears to flow out of a wetland or pond newer crossing- theres a mat at the downstream side end that keeps depth in the culvert which may be a barrier at some times missed 2 YOY EBT this it the upstream reach of Reed Brook we surveyed the downstream reach earlier in the day

No fish this small stream crosses under I-93 and North Ashland Road old dam above survey site and we quickly surveyed above and found no fish also pumphouse near dam site lots of piping running downstream high gradient likely precludes fish from repopulating the area (falls at mouth) lots of salamanders (spotted) stream temp is 14 degrees F cooler then the main stem of the Pemi River (59 vs 73) lots of macros

Bedrock/ledge cascading into pools stream almost completely shaded only organic material in stream is deciduous needles from White Pine with some oak leaves crayfish present started downstream and ended upstream at crossing

Very low gradient stream and difficult to electrofish (missed many fish) deep sections also made survey difficult cattle have access to stream crossing clogged with debris cause stream to backwater wild EBT caught by angler downstream had to skip some deeper sections

Stream flows under power line but otherwise flows through a well established forest.  Local residents built rock dam that could limit movement.  ATS presence indicates the ability for fish to move in and out of the Pemi River.  Rt. 175 crossing is slightly perched.

Culvert under Rt 119 is completely inundated with silt sand and mud which made fish passage impossible.  Water is bubbling out from below.  No fish present.  Tall grass ferns and alders covering stream banks.  Did not sample a site upstream due to lack of flow.

Drainage from road directed into stream on both sides of the crossing.  Material around the upstream end of the crossing has been washed away.  This implies that the size of the crossing is too small creating the stream to backwater.  Stream is well shaded with lots of spring seeps.  A large number of brook trout were captured.  Large amount of sand deposited near slow moving sections (bends).  An asphalt coating inside culvert is falling apart and ending up in stream.  Stream can be flashy at times (several exposed roots and undercut banks).

Stream has signs that it can be very flashy (lots of scour loose material).  Substrate mostly too large for wood to be a channel forming feature.  Lots of former channels present.  Stonewalls and foundations are nearby.  Small wetted channel compared to bankful width.  Bog Rd crossing appears to be suitable for passage.  At least three EBTs had deformities (see picture).  Scale malfunctioned no weights available.

This stream eventually flows into Campton Bog Pond (Robartwood Pond).  The crossing of Bog Rd consists of double culverts (end point of survey) that are perched.  Large area of riprap on river left side of crossing with some of it falling into stream.  Several signs that the stream can be very flashy.  Roots exposed on river right side due to steepness.  The streambanks are more gradual on the river left side and give access to a floodplain.

This is the closest we could get to the confluence with the CT River.  From this site to Rt 119 the stream consists of deep and muddy beaver flowages.  There are also beaver influences upstream of site.  Crayfish plentiful.
This survey is close to the Campton Bog Pond (Robartwood Pond).  The water temperature here was higher than at a lower survey site indicating the pond is increasing stream water temperature.
Small stream with minimal flow.  Several wood jams present from high seasonal flow.  Stream follows large hay field on the downstream side of Bog Rd.  Several undercut banks and gravel bars.

Crayfish extremely abundant.  Stream is loaded with fish (too many to capture everything).  The last 50-75 feet of reach just focused on new species.  Culvert and riprap work appear to be fairly new (last year?).

Stonewall runs along a portion of the stream bank shows historical agriculture land use practices.  The stream has good access to floodplain in this area.  The presence of ATS indicates the ability for the species to migrate from the Pemi River into Bog Brook.  ATS are not stocked in Bog Brook.

Fairly remote stream with wooded landscape throughout.  5 acre cut 150 feet from river left side allows a small amount of sun to be exposed slightly on stream.  Lots of wood accumulated in groups.  Some of the wood creates pools where substrate is suitable.  A good mix of substrate sizes that change with gradient.  Hiking trail likely made by land owner goes close to stream.  Stream has some potential for enhancement (pool creation) to grow larger trout.  A lower reach of this stream was also surveyed.

Deep and wide stream with wide/shallow runs with little current upstream has a greasy appearance on surface started at top of culvert crossing and ended at bend along road with trees corssing stream outside corner has eroding sand bank approx. 60 ft tall no trout

Beaver dams are inactive and are potential barriers at current flows.  Culvert is impassible at current flow and should be removed.  Big wild EBT.  The brook trout were found in pools and undercut banks above dams.

Flows through strip of woods through golfcourse metal-framed cart bridge over the stream with paved path which could carry storm water and sediment into stream gold course visible from stream on both sides of site end point at culvert under paved main road has approx. 2 foot cascade (saw fish pass up cascade into culvert) small discharge pipe entering stream burbot found but not captured

The Rt. 175 culvert has a cement apron that is a barrier to movement (~1.5ft high).  Powerlines cross below (~200ft) survey site.  Water intake (residential well) adjacent to stream within I foot from wetted channel.  Undercut banks and scour are signs the stream can be very flashy.  Large substrate is very loose.  No ATS indicates that there may be a barrier or high gradient outlet into the Pemi River.  ATS were found in an adjacent stream.  Good EBT reproduction many YOY.  Some trees that have been cut were in stream.  An upper reach of this stream was also surveyed.
Very small stream with just a trickle of water.  The stream went underground ~150 ft below crossing.  Fish captured were all from pool below crossing.  This is a tributary to Ash Swamp Brook.
Stream is a nursery for wild EBTs.  Frogs and water striders plentiful.

Deeply entrenched and meandering stream with likely impacts from I-93 and a large hotel on Rt 3.  Lots of trash in stream.  Cement culvert is perched (~12 inches).  Stream flows through wetland above crossing.  Fish appear to have easy access to the Pemigewassett River (the confluence is just down from the survey site and downstream from the Blair Bridge).
This stream is a very small tributary to Liscomb Brook.  There is an old stone culvert that is passable for fish.
Bridge washed out during spring flooding.  Road washed a lot of sediment into stream and moved cobble and rubble along streamside.

Another stream named Black Brook was surveyed in this watershed.  Stream consists of boulders and rubble with cascades and a few deep pools.  It levels off before going under Brook Rd potentially from the culvert backwatering.  The survey site is very close to the confluence with that stream and the Ammonoosuc River.  Mix forest around survey site but it looks like the stream flows through a large wetland complex further upstream.  Water temperatures likely preclude the presence of EBTs.

Site is situated within a large wetland/floodplain.  Alders directly on stream bank and then only grasses and shrubs beyond immediate channel.  Stream is very exposed with minimal shading but still appears to be relatively cool.  Lots of bricks along river left side.  The lower section has tall grasses that offer some shade.  Remnant beaver activity.

Flow is very stagnant with some intermittent spots.  Lots of iron and sheen on upper end.  Substrate is mostly mud.  River right side is well vegetated.  Leaf litter washed down from neighboring dwellings and parking lot.  River left side is heavily mowed with a few alders lilacs and willows.  The trees that do provide shade are large trees away from the stream.  Site appears to be impacted by deposition from culvert on downstream end.  Stream is is dry or flows underground from downstream end of site through culvert on West Main St and into cemetery.  A neighbor said a discharge pipe in the woods was leeching foamy liquid from the town safety parking lot and reaching the stream leaving a strong odor.  The smell eventually went away after some rain events.

Recently replaced culvert at top of survey reach is perched.  Water flows under the culvert.  Lots of fill from culvert replacement entering stream.  Poorly engineered crossing that should be improved.  Minimal flow above crossing.
System may be flashy during rain events as there is a lot of impervious surfaces in the area.  Lots of old litter (metal and glass).  There are two large culverts on the lower end of this site.

Well shaded stream with conifers along edge.  Trash in stream (cans and glass).  Rocks covered in short moss.  Not many large pools but mostly long riffles.  Large brush pile in stream likely caused by recent high flow.  Mink and otter tracks along stream.  Recent logging project 30 yards from the stream.  Lots of fresh sand recently deposited.  Rt. 302 is the only upstream crossing.  This stream is the outlet of Baker Pond (which may contribute to stream temperature increases).

Channel appears to have been straightened and mostly consists of riffles with very few pools.  Lawn up to edge of stream at beginning of site leaving bank erosion and no shade.  Well forested along banks upstream of housing development.  Rubble sand and gravel substrate.  Trails along both sides of the stream may indicate angling pressure.

Stream Channelized for ~50 yards upstream of crossing with riprap.  Higher flow due to recent rain.  Stream is almost entirely shaded with sandy substrate.  Large parking lot from an industrial lot near stream.  Culvert under Mt. Eustis Rd is not perched but very steep.

Recent heavy rain has caused an increased flow and may be responsible for darker tint to water.  Brook seeps into a pond at a nearby residence near end of survey site.  Some fish have black spot.  Culvert on Cherry Valley Rd appears to be suitable for fish passage.  Snowmachine bridge present near the middle of the site.
Moss covered rocks.  Nice little stream with only brook trout found.  Lots of salamanders.  A high gradient stream.

Area used by beavers.  Two remnant dams were recently removed by an excavator.  Very large dam still in place ~100 feet from upstream end of survey site.  Site is heavily shaded in 75% of the site but remains very open in areas of dams and near crossing.  Substrate is mostly sand with a few areas of gravel (near dams).  The dams cause the stream to spilt into multiple channels.

Another stream named Black Brook was also surveyed in this watershed.  Stream went from high gradient to very flat/wetland type system in survey site.  Surveyed close to where the stream enters the Ammonoosuc River.  Stream flows through large wetland that likely increases water temperature making it too warm for EBTs.  Logging occured near stream >15 years ago.  Good forested buffer throughout area.

The stream flows through a pasture in this area.  This area may have once been impounded.  Clay/silt substrate.  There is a foundation of an old stone bridge with lots of boulders and wood debris near starting point.  Very little to no shade in this section.  Other than grasses in stream there is little organic matter.  Stream is slow moving here.

Fish are in very good condition.  Although some were large they dont appear to be hatchery fish.  Site was mostly surround by softwoods but had some hardwoods mixed in.  Moss on rocks.  Could see evidence of high water from past storm (matted grasses and ferns on streambank).

No pools or wood.  Survey area consisted of a steady shallow and wide riffle that flowed over loose cobble.  Deepest area in site is ~4inches.  Very little organic material in stream.  Stream flows parallel to paved road about 20 yards away with small strip of woods.  This area is a good candidate for habitat enhancement.

Stream is impacted both by driveway and Oregon Rd.  Lots of sand and gravel washed in.  Road culvert has erosion on upstream side.  River right side has minimal buffer  between road and stream (only grasses and ferns).  The river left side has a buffer consisting of heavily forested softwoods.  The driveway culvert is slightly perched.
This is the outlet stream of Perch Pond.  Ferns and tall grasses surround most of the stream in the area.  Lots of trash (cans) in and around stream.  Stream substrate consists of sand mud and silt.
Captured just 4 juvenile BS in seine.  Population appears to be gretly reduced in 2nd year after dam removal.

BS relatively abundant in pool upstream of Ridge Road. Bridle shiner habitat remains largely intact throughout the Jones Brook watershed.  One of the least impacted watersheds in New Hampshire in terms of bridle shiner habitat.
BS found among shrubs in wetland flooded by beaver dam downstream of Ridge Road.  Unusual to see schools of BS in shrub wetland (sweet gale/meadowsweet) away from typical aquatic plant habitat.

Healthy population of BS in remote beaver impounded wetland accessed from gated snowmobile trail off of Ridge Road.  Multiple age classes among floating heart and other aquatic veg. Also observed CCS ECP and FF.
BS found upstream of beaver pond using dip nets.  One dead individual observed.
Standard warmwater sampling and collected Hg fish for DES. We used Mr.Holmans (Heidis dad) property to launch the boat. It is on Holman Rd. off of Upper Troy Rd. look for heavy machinery.
BS  extremely abundant among shallow grassy vegetation at the mouth of the Branch River in Northeast Pond in Milton.

Recently treated with herbicide for milfoil control.  Very turbid compared to clear water observed in previous surveys.  BS restricted to small remaining patch of milfoil.  No BS observed in sparse remaining pond lily and other scattered plants. Population was previously considered abundant.
Lots of wood good rocks and vegetation.  Standard warmwater assessment and des long term mercury lake
Juvenile AW found scattered along shoreline throughout lake with largest number captured just above the Lochmere Dam.  Fish began passing downstream in the last week of July.
Good shoreline vegetaion in spots dark water lots of rocks.  Was treated for milfoil and has an area buoyed off.
No BS found despite suitable habitat throughout impoundment.  Paddled from access point near bridge downstream to dam.
Post dam removal fish community survey.  Water level was moderate from recent rains but was very dry earlier in the summer.

Large number of larger brook trout found in pools because of limited flow in stream.  Stream flows along an old class VI road that is maintained to access cattle pasture upstream from survey site.  No evidence of livestock having access to stream observed.  Immediate buffer consists of alders grasses ferns white birch.  Local landowner constructed rock dam in stream.  Despite surrounding houses brook appears to be in good condition.  The culvert on Herman Savage Rd is perched (about 200 feet from start of survey).

The site is adjacent to a home where construction of a pond is underway.  There is a heavy sediment load below our sampling site from the ponds outlet stream.  The contractor of the pond indicated that a heavy localized storm caused a large amount of fill to wash into the stream recently.  They have since corrected the erosion problem to prevent future runoff.  The sediment completely embeded stream substrate well over 100m below the outlet.  The outlet stream was 6F warmer than Whipple Brook.  There was also a small gravity fed hydro with both the intake (also Whipple Brook) and outlet above the survey site.

Stream flow was high and it would have been more appropriate to have two units to sample.  Large amount of larger wood in stream.  Yellow birch beech red spruce white birch and white ash made a well established buffer in this area.  No development upstream of this survey.
Some junk/metal in stream (old saw blade tractor parts metal roofing tires barbed wire).  Some erosion along banks at bends.  Stream is in an agricultural setting but has a fairly good buffer.

Trees that had fallen into stream were recently cut with a chain saw.  Green frogs and crayfish present.  Lower portion of site is open due to hay field.  Only a small buffer of grasses and shrubs exists.  Large deposits creating extensive gravel bars.  Substrate consists of a lot of unstable sand.  ATV tracks very close to stream (right within the gravel bars).

Culverts (at the downstream end of survey site) are undersized causing aggradation at the upstream end and scour (large pool) at the downstream side.  Several land use impacts present on the river right side (no riparian buffer mowed lawn riprap to prevent further erosion small paddock on river left side but still a minimal buffer is present.  Fish appear to be in great condition.  The productivity of the stream could be related to the horse waste leaching in.  A clear trail is present between the house (river right side) and barn (river left side).  Erosion along banks was present but most areas were stable (moss present).

Stream is still very turbid from heavy localized storm a week ago.  The sediment trapped in an upstream beaver pond was likely washed down to this location.  Warm water temperatures likely preclude the presence of wild EBTs.  Culvert of Pleasant Valley Rd is perched.  Lower end of survey is much more flat and contains more silt and fine sediments than the upper more gradient section with more coarse substrate.  Immediate buffer consists of thick alders.  Minimal buffer remains beyond ~50 due to the presence of hay fields.  Several areas with matted down vegetation away from the channel indicates the recent flood was extensive.

Population of BS found in small shallow manmade pond in tributary of Lamprey River just downstream of large pool below the old Bunker Pond Dam.  Large adult BS concentrated in patches of narrow leaf pondweed and coontail.

Crossing on Lost Nation Rd is perched and has created a large deep pool.  CWS and BND were found in culvert pool but not upstream in survey location.  This may indicate that the crossing is a barrier for some fish species.  It appears that a berm was created along the stream banks a long time ago.  This may have been constructed by the removal of rocks/boulders in the stream.  Cutting and logging roads in very close proximity to stream above survey location.  Lots of older junk (including cars) along streambank.  Overall a nice stream in this area could be improved by trash removal and buffer restoration.

No perch on d/s end but downed tree created large aggregation of sediment. Green frogs. 2 lined salamanders. Can definitely observe impact of road crossing -gravel aggrad. From road on u/s side prior to culvert entrance -observed erosion and multiple splits of channel from undersized culvert. Also note gravel washing in from road.
Culvert has passage for fish but prior road washouts have caused accumulated road materials as well as increased scour to stream banks. Several springs seeping in from hillside.
Lots of sand and some vegetation.  Standard Warmwater Sample and DES long term Hg Lake
Standard Warmwater Assessment. Water very dark.

This survey should be used complimentary to the depletion surveys in other areas of the Souhegan to get a sense for lengths.  The YOY ATS present in the Souhegan were the progeny of Sea run returned adults.

This survey was conducted immediately before a large beaver dam was removed by Great Bay Trout Unlimited.  The dam was removed in an effort to reduce water temperatures in the headwaters of Thompson Brook.
AED Wadeable Streams Project
Large schools of AW in river above boat ramp.  No AW captured above Lochmere in 1,000 seconds of effort.

WATERBODY: Unnamed trib to Salmon Falls River
COMMENTS: Presence/absence survey for EBT at stream with unrestricted access to estuary.  No EBT found despite signs of groundwater influence.  Abundant AE and BND.  Very shallow narrow meandering channel with clay/silt and fine sand substrate and undercut banks. Found handgun in stream. Called police. Turned out to be an air gun.

WATERBODY: Unnamed trib to Salmon Falls River
COMMENTS: No EBT found. Stream channel eroded from excess runoff at crossing.  Culvert under RT. 4 is impassable.
Rocky ledgy meandering stream with signs of groundwater influence.  Large wood in channel undercut banks thick canopy but very low flow.  Inlet drop at culvert + perched at outlet.  Only EBT present.
Large schools of AW were repeatedly observed at dusk dimpling in this area.  We efished this area to get an understanding of the current size of the alewives.

Stream strongly influenced by wetlands (above and below crossing) and likely has summer water temperatures that preclude the presence of wild EBTs..  Very mucky substrate but some areas along the streambanks have large quantities of deposited sand.  Crossing is very undersized.

The stream is influenced by welands (above and below survey site).  Rare to see CCS as the predominant species.  Crossing consists of four small culverts with signs that flows overtop the road often.  Theres a small plunge pool downstream of the crossing.  Riparian area is well entact in this particular area but temps are liely too warm for wild EBT in the summer months.  Stream is on state property and is the outlet of Knights Meadow Marsh.

This survey site was directly upstream of the confluence with Meadow Brook.  Summer water temperature likely precludes the presence of wild EBTs.  This site flows between I89 and North Rd.  In this location there is suffienct wood buffer which is much better than other reaches of this stream where there is minimal buffer between it and North Rd.

This survey was repeated in October (same location as a survey in June) to get a sense for how fish responded to a summer with somewhat warm temperatures and limited rain.  Several female EBT appeared to have completed spawning and redds were visible.
Stream appears to be intermittent only having disconnected areas of standing water.  No fish were captured.  Well established forect canopy throughout the area.

Observed two schools of AW (one school around 1000 individuals) in main lake south of the island and in shallow section of river (above boulder embankment with deep pool).  Sample of AW comes from the smaller school.

Schools of AW observed throughout river from boat houses above trestle to confluence with Lake Winnisquam.  Extremely large school near boat houses in bend in river right before confluence with Lake.  The captured fish are not indicitive of total number captured/observed and only should be used to get current length of YOY AW.

Wind made surfacing fish hard to locate (~10mph) likely reducing catch rate.  Large schools of AW were repeatedly observed at dusk dimpling in this area.  We efished this area to get an understanding of the current size of the alewives.

This was the last survey where AW were captured.  Only 6 AW were found near Bartlett Beach.  Other locations were also surveyed (South of Leightons Point Winnipesaukee River (above Lake Winnisquam) but no AW were found.  River flow was about 600cfs and likely too strong for AW to be present.  Winnisquam is currently being refilled after the scheduled drawdown.  A survey on 11-1-12 (3000 seconds) at several locations (Winnipesaukee River upstream of Lake Winnisquam Bartlett Beach around Misquito Bridge shoreline near Ephrams Cove South of Leightons Point) and No AW were observed.
